# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: stack-canary
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Typically, buffer overflow protection modifies the organization of stack-allocated data so it includes a *canary* value that, when destroyed by a stack buffer overflow, shows that a buffer preceding it in memory has been overflowed.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] By verifying the canary value, execution of the affected program can be terminated, preventing it from misbehaving or from allowing an attacker to take control over it.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Other buffer overflow protection techniques include *bounds checking*, which checks accesses to each allocated block of memory so they cannot go beyond the actually allocated space, and *tagging*, which ensures that memory allocated for storing data cannot contain executable code.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Overfilling a buffer allocated on the stack is more likely to influence program execution than overfilling a buffer on the heap because the stack contains the return addresses for all active function calls.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] However, similar implementation-specific protections also exist against heap-based overflows.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] There are several implementations of buffer overflow protection, including those for the GNU Compiler Collection, LLVM, Microsoft Visual Studio, and other compilers.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] A stack buffer overflow occurs when a program writes to a memory address on the program's call stack outside of the intended data structure, which is usually a fixed-length buffer.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Stack buffer overflow bugs are caused when a program writes more data to a buffer located on the stack than what is actually allocated for that buffer.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] This almost always results in corruption of adjacent data on the stack, and in cases where the overflow was triggered by mistake, will often cause the program to crash or operate incorrectly.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Stack buffer overflow is a type of the more general programming malfunction known as buffer overflow (or buffer overrun).
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Overfilling a buffer on the stack is more likely to derail program execution than overfilling a buffer on the heap because the stack contains the return addresses for all active function calls.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Stack buffer overflow can be caused deliberately as part of an attack known as stack smashing.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] This is one of the oldest and more reliable methods for attackers to gain unauthorized access to a computer.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Typically, buffer overflow protection modifies the organization of data in the stack frame of a function call to include a "canary" value that, when destroyed, shows that a buffer preceding it in memory has been overflowed.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] This provides the benefit of preventing an entire class of attacks.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] According to some researchers, the performance impact of these techniques is negligible.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Stack-smashing protection is unable to protect against certain forms of attack.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] For example, it cannot protect against buffer overflows in the heap.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] There is no sane way to alter the layout of data within a structure; structures are expected to be the same between modules, especially with shared libraries.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Any data in a structure after a buffer is impossible to protect with canaries; thus, programmers must be very careful about how they organize their variables and use their structures.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] The terminology is a reference to the historic practice of using canaries in coal mines, since they would be affected by toxic gases earlier than the miners, thus providing a biological warning system.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Canaries are alternately known as *stack cookies*, which is meant to evoke the image of a "broken cookie" when the value is corrupted.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] There are three types of canaries in use: *terminator*, *random*, and *random XOR*.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Current versions of StackGuard support all three, while ProPolice supports *terminator* and *random* canaries.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Normally, a random canary is generated at program initialization, and stored in a global variable.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] This variable is usually padded by unmapped pages so that attempting to read it using any kinds of tricks that exploit bugs to read off RAM cause a segmentation fault, terminating the program.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] It may still be possible to read the canary if the attacker knows where it is or can get the program to read from the stack.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Random XOR canaries have the same vulnerabilities as random canaries, except that the "read from stack" method of getting the canary is a bit more complicated.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] The attacker must get the canary, the algorithm, and the control data in order to re-generate the original canary needed to spoof the protection.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] In addition, random XOR canaries can protect against a certain type of attack involving overflowing a buffer in a structure into a pointer to change the pointer to point at a piece of control data.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Because of the XOR encoding, the canary will be wrong if the control data or return value is changed.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Because of the pointer, the control data or return value can be changed without overflowing over the canary.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Although these canaries protect the control data from being altered by clobbered pointers, they do not protect any other data or the pointers themselves.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Function pointers especially are a problem here, as they can be overflowed into and can execute shellcode when called.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Bounds checking is a compiler-based technique that adds run-time bounds information for each allocated block of memory, and checks all pointers against those at run-time.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] For C and C++, bounds checking can be performed at pointer calculation time or at dereference time.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Implementations of this approach use either a central repository, which describes each allocated block of memory, or fat pointers, which contain both the pointer and additional data, describing the region that they point to.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Tagging is a compiler-based or hardware-based (requiring a tagged architecture) technique for tagging the type of a piece of data in memory, used mainly for type checking.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] By marking certain areas of memory as non-executable, it effectively prevents memory allocated to store data from containing executable code.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Also, certain areas of memory can be marked as non-allocated, preventing buffer overflows.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Historically, tagging has been used for implementing high-level programming languages; with appropriate support from the operating system, tagging can also be used to detect buffer overflows.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] An example is the NX bit hardware feature, supported by Intel, AMD and ARM processors.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Stack-smashing protection was first implemented by *StackGuard* in 1997, and published at the 1998 USENIX Security Symposium.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] StackGuard was introduced as a set of patches to the Intel x86 backend of GCC 2.7.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] StackGuard was maintained for the Immunix Linux distribution from 1998 to 2003, and was extended with implementations for terminator, random and random XOR canaries.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] StackGuard was suggested for inclusion in GCC 3.x at the GCC 2003 Summit Proceedings, but this was never achieved.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] From 2001 to 2005, IBM developed GCC patches for stack-smashing protection, known as *ProPolice*.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] It improved on the idea of StackGuard by placing buffers after local pointers and function arguments in the stack frame.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] This helped avoid the corruption of pointers, preventing access to arbitrary memory locations.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Red Hat engineers identified problems with ProPolice though, and in 2005 re-implemented stack-smashing protection for inclusion in GCC 4.1.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] This work introduced the -fstack-protector flag, which protects only some vulnerable functions, and the -fstack-protector-all flag, which protects all functions whether they need it or not.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] In 2012, Google engineers implemented the -fstack-protector-strong flag to strike a better balance between security and performance.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] This flag protects more kinds of vulnerable functions than -fstack-protector does, but not every function, providing better performance than -fstack-protector-all.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] It is available in GCC since its version 4.9.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] All Fedora packages are compiled with -fstack-protector since Fedora Core 5, and -fstack-protector-strong since Fedora 20.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Most packages in Ubuntu are compiled with -fstack-protector since 6.10.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Every Arch Linux package is compiled with -fstack-protector since 2011.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] All Arch Linux packages built since 4 May 2014 use -fstack-protector-strong.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Stack protection is only used for some packages in Debian, and only for the FreeBSD base system since 8.0.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Stack protection is standard in certain operating systems, including OpenBSD, Hardened Gentoo and DragonFly BSD.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] StackGuard and ProPolice cannot protect against overflows in automatically allocated structures that overflow into function pointers.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] ProPolice at least will rearrange the allocation order to get such structures allocated before function pointers.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] A separate mechanism for pointer protection was proposed in PointGuard and is available on Microsoft Windows.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] The compiler suite from Microsoft implements buffer overflow protection since version 2003 through the /GS command-line switch, which is enabled by default since version 2005.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Stack-smashing protection can be turned on by the compiler flag `-qstackprotect`.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Clang supports the same -fstack-protector options as GCC and a stronger "safe stack" (-fsanitize=safe-stack) system with similarly low performance impact.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Clang also has three buffer overflow detectors, namely AddressSanitizer (`-fsanitize=address`), UBSan (`-fsanitize=bounds`), and the unofficial SafeCode (last updated for LLVM 3.0).
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] These systems have different tradeoffs in terms of performance penalty, memory overhead, and classes of detected bugs.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Stack protection is standard in certain operating systems, including OpenBSD.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Intel's C and C++ compiler supports stack-smashing protection with options similar to those provided by GCC and Microsoft Visual Studio.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Invented by Mike Frantzen, StackGhost is a simple tweak to the register window spill–fill routines which makes buffer overflows much more difficult to exploit.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] The performance impact is negligible: less than one percent.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] The resulting gdb issues were resolved by Mark Kettenis two years later, allowing enabling of the feature.
[src:stack-canary/buffer-overflow-protection] Following this event, the StackGhost code was integrated (and optimized) into the SPARC version of the OpenBSD operating system.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] Memory errors were first considered in the context of resource management (computing) and time-sharing systems, in an effort to avoid problems such as fork bombs.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] Developments were mostly theoretical until the Morris worm, which exploited a buffer overflow in fingerd.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] The field of computer security developed quickly thereafter, escalating with multitudes of new attacks such as the return-to-libc attack and defense techniques such as the non-executable stack and address space layout randomization.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] Randomization prevents most buffer overflow attacks and requires the attacker to use heap spraying or other application-dependent methods to obtain addresses, although its adoption has been slow.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] However, deployments of the technology are typically limited to randomizing libraries and the location of the stack.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] In 2019, a Microsoft security engineer reported that 70% of all security vulnerabilities were caused by memory safety issues.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] In 2020, a team at Google similarly reported that 70% of all "severe security bugs" in Chromium were caused by memory safety problems.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] Many other high-profile vulnerabilities and exploits in critical software have ultimately stemmed from a lack of memory safety, including Heartbleed and a long-standing privilege escalation bug in sudo.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] The pervasiveness and severity of vulnerabilities and exploits arising from memory safety issues have led several security researchers to describe identifying memory safety issues as "shooting fish in a barrel".
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] Some modern high-level programming languages are memory-safe by default, though not completely since they only check their own code and not the system they interact with.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] Automatic memory management in the form of garbage collection is the most common technique for preventing some of the memory safety problems, since it prevents common memory safety errors like use-after-free for all data allocated within the language runtime.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] However, the performance overhead of garbage collection makes these languages unsuitable for certain performance-critical applications.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] For languages that use manual memory management, memory safety is not usually guaranteed by the runtime.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] Instead, memory safety properties must either be guaranteed by the compiler via static program analysis and automated theorem proving or carefully managed by the programmer at runtime.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] For example, the Rust programming language implements a borrow checker to ensure memory safety, while C and C++ provide no memory safety guarantees.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] The substantial amount of software written in C and C++ has motivated the development of external static analysis tools like Coverity, which offers static memory analysis for C.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] DieHard, its redesign DieHarder, and the Allinea Distributed Debugging Tool are special heap allocators that allocate objects in their own random virtual memory page, allowing invalid reads and writes to be stopped and debugged at the exact instruction that causes them.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] Protection relies upon hardware memory protection and thus overhead is typically not substantial, although it can grow significantly if the program makes heavy use of allocation.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] Randomization provides only probabilistic protection against memory errors, but can often be easily implemented in existing software by relinking the binary.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] The memcheck tool of Valgrind uses an instruction set simulator and runs the compiled program in a memory-checking virtual machine, providing guaranteed detection of a subset of runtime memory errors.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] However, it typically slows the program down by a factor of 40, and furthermore must be explicitly informed of custom memory allocators.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] With access to the source code, libraries exist that collect and track legitimate values for pointers ("metadata") and check each pointer access against the metadata for validity, such as the Boehm garbage collector.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] In general, memory safety can be safely assured using tracing garbage collection and the insertion of runtime checks on every memory access; this approach has overhead, but less than that of Valgrind.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] All garbage-collected languages take this approach.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] For C and C++, many tools exist that perform a compile-time transformation of the code to do memory safety checks at runtime, such as CheckPointer and AddressSanitizer which imposes an average slowdown factor of 2.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] BoundWarden is a new spatial memory enforcement approach that utilizes a combination of compile-time transformation and runtime concurrent monitoring techniques.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] Fuzz testing is well-suited for finding memory safety bugs and is often used in combination with dynamic checkers such as AddressSanitizer.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] Some lists may also include **race conditions** (concurrent reads/writes to shared memory) as being part of memory safety (e.g., for access control).
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] The Rust programming language prevents many kinds of memory-based race conditions by default, because it ensures there is at most one writer *or* one or more readers.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] Many other programming languages, such as Java, do *not* automatically prevent memory-based race conditions, yet are still generally considered "memory safe" languages.
[src:stack-canary/memory-safety] Therefore, countering race conditions is generally *not* considered necessary for a language to be considered memory safe.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Additionally, a peek operation can, without modifying the stack, return the value of the last element added (the item at the top of the stack).
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] The name *stack* is an analogy to a set of physical items stacked one atop another, such as a stack of plates.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] The order in which elements are added to or removed from a stack is described as **last in, first out**, referred to by the acronym **LIFO**.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] As with a stack of physical objects, this structure makes it easy to take an item off the top of the stack, but accessing a datum deeper in the stack may require removing multiple other items first.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Considered a sequential collection, a stack has one end which is the only position at which the push and pop operations may occur, the *top* of the stack, and is fixed at the other end, the *bottom*.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] A stack may be implemented as, for example, a singly linked list with a pointer to the top element.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] A stack may be implemented to have a bounded capacity.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] If the stack is full and does not contain enough space to accept another element, the stack is in a state of stack overflow.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Stacks entered the computer science literature in 1946, when Alan Turing used the terms "bury" and "unbury" as a means of calling and returning from subroutines.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Subroutines and a two-level stack had already been implemented in Konrad Zuse's Z4 in 1945.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Bauer of the Technical University of Munich proposed the idea of a stack called *Operationskeller* ("operational cellar") in 1955 and filed a patent in 1957.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] In March 1988, by which time Samelson was deceased, Bauer received the IEEE Computer Pioneer Award for the invention of the stack principle.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Similar concepts were independently developed by Charles Leonard Hamblin in the first half of 1954 and by Wilhelm Kämmerer with his *automatisches Gedächtnis* ("automatic memory") in 1958.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Stacks are often described using the analogy of a spring-loaded stack of plates in a cafeteria.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Clean plates are placed on top of the stack, pushing down any plates already there.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] When the top plate is removed from the stack, the one below it is elevated to become the new top plate.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] In many implementations, a stack has more operations than the essential "push" and "pop" operations.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] An example of a non-essential operation is "top of stack", or "peek", which observes the top element without removing it from the stack.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Since this can be broken down into a "pop" followed by a "push" to return the same data to the stack, it is not considered an essential operation.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] If the stack is empty, an underflow condition will occur upon execution of either the "peek" or "pop" operation.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Additionally, many implementations include convenience operations that handle common tasks, such as checking if the stack is empty or returning its size.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] A stack can be easily implemented either through an array or a linked list, as it is merely a special case of a list.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] In either case, what identifies the data structure as a stack is not the implementation but the interface: the user is only allowed to pop or push items onto the array or linked list, with few other helper operations.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] The following will demonstrate both implementations using pseudocode.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] An array can be used to implement a (bounded) stack, as follows.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] The first element, usually at the zero offset, is the bottom, resulting in `array[0]` being the first element pushed onto the stack and the last element popped off.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] The program must keep track of the size (length) of the stack, using a variable *top* that records the number of items pushed so far, therefore pointing to the place in the array where the next element is to be inserted (assuming a zero-based index convention).
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Using a dynamic array, it is possible to implement a stack that can grow or shrink as much as needed.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] The size of the stack is simply the size of the dynamic array, which is a very efficient implementation of a stack since adding items to or removing items from the end of a dynamic array requires amortized O(1) time.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Another option for implementing stacks is to use a singly linked list.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Some languages, such as Perl, LISP, JavaScript and Python, make the stack operations push and pop available on their standard list/array types.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Some languages, notably those in the Forth family (including PostScript), are designed around language-defined stacks that are directly visible to and manipulated by the programmer.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Several of the C++ Standard Library container types have `push_back()` and `pop_back()` operations with LIFO semantics; additionally, the `std::stack` template class adapts existing containers to provide a restricted API with only push/pop operations.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Java's library contains a `Stack` class that is a specialization of `Vector`.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Following is an example program in Java language, using that class.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Some processors, such as the PDP-11, VAX, and Motorola 68000 series have addressing modes useful for stack manipulation.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] The following trivial PDP-11 assembly source code pushes two numbers on a stack and adds them, leaving the result on the stack.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] A common use of stacks at the architecture level is as a means of allocating and accessing memory.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] A typical stack is an area of computer memory with a fixed origin and a variable size.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Initially the size of the stack is zero.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] A stack pointer (usually in the form of a processor register) points to the most recently referenced location on the stack; when the stack has a size of zero, the stack pointer points to the origin of the stack.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] There are many variations on the basic principle of stack operations.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Every stack has a fixed location in memory at which it begins.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] As data items are added to the stack, the stack pointer is displaced to indicate the current extent of the stack, which expands away from the origin.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Stack pointers may point to the origin of a stack or to a limited range of addresses above or below the origin (depending on the direction in which the stack grows); however, the stack pointer cannot cross the origin of the stack.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] In other words, if the origin of the stack is at address 1000 and the stack grows downwards (towards addresses 999, 998, and so on), the stack pointer must never be incremented beyond 1000 (to 1001 or beyond).
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] If a pop operation on the stack causes the stack pointer to move past the origin of the stack, a *stack underflow* occurs.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] If a push operation causes the stack pointer to increment or decrement beyond the maximum extent of the stack, a *stack overflow* occurs.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Stacks are often visualized growing from the bottom up (like real-world stacks).
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] They may also be visualized growing from left to right, where the top is on the far right, or even growing from top to bottom.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] The important feature is for the bottom of the stack to be in a fixed position.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] The illustration in this section is an example of a top-to-bottom growth visualization: the top (28) is the stack "bottom", since the stack "top" (9) is where items are pushed or popped from.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] A *right rotate* will move the first element to the third position, the second to the first and the third to the second.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] A stack is usually represented in computers by a block of memory cells, with the "bottom" at a fixed location, and the stack pointer holding the address of the current "top" cell in the stack.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] The "top" and "bottom" nomenclature is used irrespective of whether the stack actually grows towards higher memory addresses.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Pushing an item on to the stack adjusts the stack pointer by the size of the item (either decrementing or incrementing, depending on the direction in which the stack grows in memory), pointing it to the next cell, and copies the new top item to the stack area.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Depending again on the exact implementation, at the end of a push operation, the stack pointer may point to the next unused location in the stack, or it may point to the topmost item in the stack.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] If the stack points to the current topmost item, the stack pointer will be updated before a new item is pushed onto the stack; if it points to the next available location in the stack, it will be updated *after* the new item is pushed onto the stack.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Popping the stack is simply the inverse of pushing.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] The topmost item in the stack is removed and the stack pointer is updated, in the opposite order of that used in the push operation.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Many CISC-type CPU designs, including the x86, Z80 and 6502, have a dedicated register for use as the call stack stack pointer with dedicated call, return, push, and pop instructions that implicitly update the dedicated register, thus increasing code density.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Some CISC processors, like the PDP-11 and the 68000, also have special addressing modes for implementation of stacks, typically with a semi-dedicated stack pointer as well (such as A7 in the 68000).
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] In contrast, most RISC CPU designs do not have dedicated stack instructions and therefore most, if not all, registers may be used as stack pointers as needed.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Some machines use a stack for arithmetic and logical operations; operands are pushed onto the stack, and arithmetic and logical operations act on the top one or more items on the stack, popping them off the stack and pushing the result onto the stack.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Machines that function in this fashion are called stack machines.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] A number of mainframes and minicomputers were stack machines, the most famous being the Burroughs Large Systems.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Other examples include the CISC HP 3000 machines and the CISC machines from Tandem Computers.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] The x87 floating-point architecture is an example of a set of registers organised as a stack where direct access to individual registers (relative to the current top) is also possible.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Having the top-of-stack as an implicit argument allows for a small machine code footprint with a good usage of bus bandwidth and code caches, but it also prevents some types of optimizations possible on processors permitting random access to the register file for all (two or three) operands.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] A stack structure also makes superscalar implementations with register renaming (for speculative execution) somewhat more complex to implement, although it is still feasible, as exemplified by modern x87 implementations.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Sun SPARC, AMD Am29000, and Intel i960 are all examples of architectures that use register windows within a register-stack as another strategy to avoid the use of slow main memory for function arguments and return values.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] There is also a number of small microprocessors that implement a stack directly in hardware, and some microcontrollers have a fixed-depth stack that is not directly accessible.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Examples are the PIC microcontrollers, the Computer Cowboys MuP21, the Harris RTX line, and the Novix NC4016.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] At least one microcontroller family, the COP400, implements a stack either directly in hardware or in RAM via a stack pointer, depending on the device.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Many stack-based microprocessors were used to implement the programming language Forth at the microcode level.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Calculators that employ reverse Polish notation use a stack structure to hold values.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Expressions can be represented in prefix, postfix or infix notations and conversion from one form to another may be accomplished using a stack.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Many compilers use a stack to parse syntax before translation into low-level code.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Most programming languages are context-free languages, allowing them to be parsed with stack-based machines.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Another important application of stacks is backtracking.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] An illustration of this is the simple example of finding the correct path in a maze that contains a series of points, a starting point, several paths and a destination.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] If random paths must be chosen, then after following an incorrect path, there must be a method by which to return to the beginning of that path.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] This can be achieved through the use of stacks, as a last correct point can be pushed onto the stack, and popped from the stack in case of an incorrect path.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] The prototypical example of a backtracking algorithm is depth-first search, which finds all vertices of a graph that can be reached from a specified starting vertex.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Other applications of backtracking involve searching through spaces that represent potential solutions to an optimization problem.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Branch and bound is a technique for performing such backtracking searches without exhaustively searching all of the potential solutions in such a space.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] A number of programming languages are stack-oriented, meaning they define most basic operations (adding two numbers, printing a character) as taking their arguments from the stack, and placing any return values back on the stack.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] For example, PostScript has a return stack and an operand stack, and also has a graphics state stack and a dictionary stack.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Many virtual machines are also stack-oriented, including the p-code machine and the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] The functions follow a runtime protocol between caller and callee to save arguments and return value on the stack.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Stacks are an important way of supporting nested or recursive function calls.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] This type of stack is used implicitly by the compiler to support CALL and RETURN statements (or their equivalents) and is not manipulated directly by the programmer.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Some programming languages use the stack to store data that is local to a procedure.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Space for local data items is allocated from the stack when the procedure is entered, and is deallocated when the procedure exits.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] The C programming language is typically implemented in this way.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Using the same stack for both data and procedure calls has important security implications (see below) of which a programmer must be aware in order to avoid introducing serious security bugs into a program.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Several algorithms use a stack (separate from the usual function call stack of most programming languages) as the principal data structure with which they organize their information.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Some computing environments use stacks in ways that may make them vulnerable to security breaches and attacks.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Programmers working in such environments must take special care to avoid such pitfalls in these implementations.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] As an example, some programming languages use a common stack to store both data local to a called procedure and the linking information that allows the procedure to return to its caller.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] This means that the program moves data into and out of the same stack that contains critical return addresses for the procedure calls.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] If data is moved to the wrong location on the stack, or an oversized data item is moved to a stack location that is not large enough to contain it, return information for procedure calls may be corrupted, causing the program to fail.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Malicious parties may attempt a stack smashing attack that takes advantage of this type of implementation by providing oversized data input to a program that does not check the length of input.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Such a program may copy the data in its entirety to a location on the stack, and in doing so, it may change the return addresses for procedures that have called it.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] This type of attack is a variation on the buffer overflow attack and is an extremely frequent source of security breaches in software, mainly because some of the most popular compilers use a shared stack for both data and procedure calls, and do not verify the length of data items.
[src:stack-canary/stack-abstract-data-type] Frequently, programmers do not write code to verify the size of data items, either, and when an oversized or undersized data item is copied to the stack, a security breach may occur.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] In software, a **stack buffer overflow** or **stack buffer overrun** occurs when a program writes to a memory address on the program's call stack outside of the intended data structure, which is usually a fixed-length buffer.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] A stack buffer overflow can be caused deliberately as part of an attack known as **stack smashing**.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] If the affected program is running with special privileges, or accepts data from untrusted network hosts (e.g. a webserver) then the bug is a potential security vulnerability.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] If the stack buffer is filled with data supplied from an untrusted user then that user can corrupt the stack in such a way as to inject executable code into the running program and take control of the process.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] The canonical method for exploiting a stack-based buffer overflow is to overwrite the function return address with a pointer to attacker-controlled data (usually on the stack itself).
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] This code takes an argument from the command line and copies it to a local stack variable `c`.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] This works fine for command-line arguments smaller than 12 characters (as can be seen in figure B below).
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] Any arguments larger than 11 characters long will result in corruption of the stack.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] (The maximum number of characters that is safe is one less than the size of the buffer here because in the C programming language, strings are terminated by a null byte character.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] A twelve-character input thus requires thirteen bytes to store, the input followed by the sentinel zero byte.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] In figure C above, when an argument larger than 11 bytes is supplied on the command line `foo()` overwrites local stack data, the saved frame pointer, and most importantly, the return address.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] When `foo()` returns, it pops the return address off the stack and jumps to that address (i.e. starts executing instructions from that address).
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] Thus, the attacker has overwritten the return address with a pointer to the stack buffer `char c[12]`, which now contains attacker-supplied data.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] In an actual stack buffer overflow exploit the string of "A"'s would instead be shellcode suitable to the platform and desired function.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] If this program had special privileges (e.g. the SUID bit set to run as the superuser), then the attacker could use this vulnerability to gain superuser privileges on the affected machine.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] The attacker can also modify internal variable values to exploit some bugs.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] There are typically two methods that are used to alter the stored address in the stack - direct and indirect.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] Attackers started developing indirect attacks, which have fewer dependencies, in order to bypass protection measures that were made to reduce direct attacks.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] A number of platforms have subtle differences in their implementation of the call stack that can affect the way a stack buffer overflow exploit will work.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] Some machine architectures store the top-level return address of the call stack in a register.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] This means that any overwritten return address will not be used until a later unwinding of the call stack.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] Another example of a machine-specific detail that can affect the choice of exploitation techniques is the fact that most RISC-style machine architectures will not allow unaligned access to memory.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] Combined with a fixed length for machine opcodes, this machine limitation can make the technique of jumping to the stack almost impossible to implement (with the one exception being when the program actually contains the unlikely code to explicitly jump to the stack register).
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] Within the topic of stack buffer overflows, an often-discussed-but-rarely-seen architecture is one in which the stack grows in the opposite direction.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] This change in architecture is frequently suggested as a solution to the stack buffer overflow problem because any overflow of a stack buffer that occurs within the same stack frame cannot overwrite the return pointer.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] However, any overflow that occurs in a buffer from a previous stack frame will still overwrite a return pointer and allow for malicious exploitation of the bug.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] For instance, in the example above, the return pointer for `foo` will not be overwritten because the overflow actually occurs within the stack frame for `memcpy`.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] However, because the buffer that overflows during the call to `memcpy` resides in a previous stack frame, the return pointer for `memcpy` will have a numerically higher memory address than the buffer.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] This means that instead of the return pointer for `foo` being overwritten, the return pointer for `memcpy` will be overwritten.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] At most, this means that growing the stack in the opposite direction will change some details of how stack buffer overflows are exploitable, but it will not reduce significantly the number of exploitable bugs.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] Over the years, a number of control-flow integrity schemes have been developed to inhibit malicious stack buffer overflow exploitation.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] Stack canaries, named for their analogy to a canary in a coal mine, are used to detect a stack buffer overflow before execution of malicious code can occur.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] This method works by placing a small integer, the value of which is randomly chosen at program start, in memory just before the stack return pointer.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] Most buffer overflows overwrite memory from lower to higher memory addresses, so in order to overwrite the return pointer (and thus take control of the process) the canary value must also be overwritten.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] This value is checked to make sure it has not changed before a routine uses the return pointer on the stack.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] This technique can greatly increase the difficulty of exploiting a stack buffer overflow because it forces the attacker to gain control of the instruction pointer by some non-traditional means such as corrupting other important variables on the stack.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] Another approach to preventing stack buffer overflow exploitation is to enforce a memory policy on the stack memory region that disallows execution from the stack (W^X, "Write XOR Execute").
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] This means that in order to execute shellcode from the stack an attacker must either find a way to disable the execution protection from memory, or find a way to put their shellcode payload in a non-protected region of memory.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] This method is becoming more popular now that hardware support for the no-execute flag is available in most desktop processors.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] While this method prevents the canonical stack smashing exploit, stack overflows can be exploited in other ways.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] First, it is common to find ways to store shellcode in unprotected memory regions like the heap, and so very little need change in the way of exploitation.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] Another attack is the so-called return to libc method for shellcode creation.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] In this attack the malicious payload will load the stack not with shellcode, but with a proper call stack so that execution is vectored to a chain of standard library calls, usually with the effect of disabling memory execute protections and allowing shellcode to run as normal.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] This works because the execution never actually vectors to the stack itself.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] A variant of return-to-libc is return-oriented programming (ROP), which sets up a series of return addresses, each of which executes a small sequence of cherry-picked machine instructions within the existing program code or system libraries, sequence which ends with a return.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] These so-called *gadgets* each accomplish some simple register manipulation or similar execution before returning, and stringing them together achieves the attacker's ends.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] It is even possible to use "returnless" return-oriented programming by exploiting instructions or groups of instructions that behave much like a return instruction.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] Instead of separating the code from the data, another mitigation technique is to introduce randomization to the memory space of the executing program.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] Since the attacker needs to determine where executable code that can be used resides, either an executable payload is provided (with an executable stack) or one is constructed using code reuse such as in ret2libc or return-oriented programming (ROP).
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] Randomizing the memory layout will, as a concept, prevent the attacker from knowing where any code is.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] However, implementations typically will not randomize everything; usually the executable itself is loaded at a fixed address and hence even when ASLR (address space layout randomization) is combined with a non-executable stack the attacker can use this fixed region of memory.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] Therefore, all programs should be compiled with PIE (position-independent executables) such that even this region of memory is randomized.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] The entropy of the randomization is different from implementation to implementation and a low enough entropy can in itself be a problem in terms of brute forcing the memory space that is randomized.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] The previous mitigations make the steps of the exploitation harder.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] But it is still possible to exploit a stack buffer overflow if some vulnerabilities are presents or if some conditions are met.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] An attacker is able to exploit the format string vulnerability for revealing the memory locations in the vulnerable program.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] When Data Execution Prevention is enabled to forbid any execute access to the stack, the attacker can still use the overwritten return address (the instruction pointer) to point to data in a code segment (.text on Linux) or every other executable section of the program.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] Consists to overwrite the return pointer a bit before a return instruction (ret in x86) of the program.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] The instructions between the new return pointer and the return instruction will be executed and the return instruction will return to the payload controlled by the exploiter.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] Jump Oriented Programming is a technique that uses jump instructions to reuse code instead of the ret instruction.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] A limitation of ASLR realization on 64-bit systems is that it is vulnerable to memory disclosure and information leakage attacks.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] The attacker can launch the ROP by revealing a single function address using information leakage attack.
[src:stack-canary/stack-buffer-overflow] The following section describes the similar existing strategy for breaking down the ASLR protection.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] A typical exploit uses a combination of these techniques to take control of the instruction pointer (IP) of a process, for example by forcing a program to overwrite the address of a library function or the return address on the stack with a pointer to some malicious shellcode.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] The padding parameters to format specifiers are used to control the number of bytes output and the `%x` token is used to pop bytes from the stack until the beginning of the format string itself is reached.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] The start of the format string is crafted to contain the address that the `%n` format token can then overwrite with the address of the malicious code to execute.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] This is a common vulnerability because format bugs were previously thought harmless and resulted in vulnerabilities in many common tools.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] MITRE's CVE project lists roughly 500 vulnerable programs as of June 2007, and a trend analysis ranks it the 9th most-reported vulnerability type between 2001 and 2006.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] Format string bugs most commonly appear when a programmer wishes to output a string containing user supplied data (either to a file, to a buffer, or to the user).
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] The programmer may mistakenly write `printf(buffer)` instead of `printf("%s", buffer)`.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] The first version interprets `buffer` as a format string, and parses any formatting instructions it may contain.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] The second version simply prints a string to the screen, as the programmer intended.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] Both versions behave identically in the absence of format specifiers in the string, which makes it easy for the mistake to go unnoticed by the developer.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] Format bugs arise because C's argument passing conventions are not type-safe.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] In particular, the `varargs` mechanism allows functions to accept any number of arguments (e.g.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] `printf`) by "popping" as many arguments off the call stack as they wish, trusting the early arguments to indicate how many additional arguments are to be popped, and of what types.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] Format string bugs can occur in other programming languages besides C, such as Perl, although they appear with less frequency and usually cannot be exploited to execute code of the attacker's choice.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] Format bugs were first noted in 1989 by the fuzz testing work done at the University of Wisconsin, which discovered an "interaction effect" in the C shell (csh) between its command history mechanism and an error routine that assumed safe string input.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] The use of format string bugs as an attack vector was discovered in September 1999 by Tymm Twillman during a security audit of the ProFTPD daemon.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] The audit uncovered an `snprintf` that directly passed user-generated data without a format string.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] Extensive tests with contrived arguments to printf-style functions showed that it was possible to use this for privilege escalation.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] This led to the first posting in September 1999 on the Bugtraq mailing list regarding this class of vulnerabilities, including a basic exploit.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] It was still several months, however, before the security community became aware of the full dangers of format string vulnerabilities as exploits for other software using this method began to surface.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] The first exploits that brought the issue to common awareness (by providing remote root access via code execution) were published simultaneously on the Bugtraq list in June 2000 by Przemysław Frasunek and a person using the nickname *tf8*.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] They were shortly followed by an explanation, posted by a person using the nickname *lamagra*.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] "Format bugs" was posted to the Bugtraq list by Pascal Bouchareine in July 2000.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] The seminal paper "Format String Attacks" by Tim Newsham was published in September 2000 and other detailed technical explanation papers were published in September 2001 such as *Exploiting Format String Vulnerabilities*, by team Teso.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] Many compilers can statically check format strings and produce warnings for dangerous or suspect formats.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] In the GNU Compiler Collection, the relevant compiler flags are, `-Wall`,`-Wformat`, `-Wno-format-extra-args`, `-Wformat-security`, `-Wformat-nonliteral`, and `-Wformat=2`.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] Most of these are only useful for detecting bad format strings that are known at compile-time.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] If the format string may come from the user or from a source external to the application, the application must validate the format string before using it.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] Care must also be taken if the application generates or selects format strings on the fly.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] If the GNU C library is used, the `-D_FORTIFY_SOURCE=2` parameter can be used to detect certain types of attacks occurring at run-time.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] The `-Wformat-nonliteral` check is more stringent.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] Contrary to many other security issues, the root cause of format string vulnerabilities is relatively easy to detect in x86-compiled executables: For `printf`-family functions, proper use implies a separate argument for the format string and the arguments to be formatted.
[src:stack-canary/uncontrolled-format-string] Faulty uses of such functions can be spotted by simply counting the number of arguments passed to the function; an "argument deficiency" is then a strong indicator that the function was misused.
